  "texts": [
    "This has motivated different strategies to activate second-order responses in nominally centrosymmetric 2D materials, including controlled strain [18][19][20][21], stacking engineering and twist angles [22][23][24], and out-of-plane electric fields [25,26].",
    "However, while electrically tunable SHG, including electricfield-induced second-harmonic (EFISH) responses where a static field activates an effective χ (2) ∝ χ (3) E DC, has been widely studied [17,[26][27][28][29], the corresponding fieldinduced BPVE remains comparatively unexplored.A first step in this direction was taken by Zheng et al. [25], who investigated field-induced shift and injection currents in AA ′ -and AB-stacked bilayer graphene using a four-band π-orbital tight-binding model [17,30,31].",
    "Their results showed that breaking inversion symmetry via a perpendicular gate indeed generates finite dc photocurrents.",
    "Yet two limitations complicate the interpretation.",
    "First, pristine AA stacking is a semimetal, thus the applied field simultaneously open a gap and break inversion, making it difficult to separate symmetry effects from semimetal-to-semiconductor transitions."
